WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.720
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:21.510 --> 00:00:24.670
[ Applause ]

00:00:24.670 --> 00:00:26.390
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: Welcome.

00:00:26.390 --> 00:00:28.770
[ Applause ]

00:00:28.770 --> 00:00:32.470
Welcome to the Library of Congress.

00:00:32.470 --> 00:00:37.740
The Library of Congress is
the world's largest library,

00:00:37.740 --> 00:00:45.790
162 million items,
836 miles of shelving.

00:00:45.790 --> 00:00:52.790
And it's also the home to
historic recordings and movies.

00:00:52.790 --> 00:00:54.610
And the Library of Congress

00:00:54.610 --> 00:01:00.380
for the first time is celebrating
a very interesting era in music.

00:01:00.380 --> 00:01:04.240
I happen to live through it.

00:01:04.240 --> 00:01:06.460
[ Laughter ]

00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:11.940
And we had a presentation
on fashion in the '70s.

00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:15.510
And I kept saying that
is an oxymoron.

00:01:15.510 --> 00:01:18.090
[ Laughter ]

00:01:18.090 --> 00:01:20.620
One of the best things though
about living through it

00:01:20.620 --> 00:01:22.680
and reviewing the fashion

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:27.660
and the recordings though is
we could have crazy fashion

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:30.790
because we had such great music.

00:01:30.790 --> 00:01:35.350
We were all thinner
because we danced all night.

00:01:35.350 --> 00:01:41.170
And we really have contributed I
think in our generation and some

00:01:41.170 --> 00:01:44.570
of my colleagues are here
that lived through it too,

00:01:44.570 --> 00:01:49.220
to showcasing the range and
diversity of recorded sound.

00:01:49.220 --> 00:01:53.960
I'd like to greet live stream
viewers on Facebook and YouTube.

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:56.060
Thank you all for joining us.

00:01:56.060 --> 00:02:01.000
And today's symposium explores
the cultural significance

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.750 position:56%
and the legacy of the disco culture.

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:06.350
You'll hear from a range
of distinguished speakers

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:11.040
from the music world, academia
and broadcast journalism.

00:02:11.040 --> 00:02:16.650
We're so thankful to be hosting
this wonderful celebration

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:20.620
with cultural institutions and
other organizations including The

00:02:20.620 --> 00:02:26.150
Recording Academy, brightest
young things we were back then.

00:02:26.150 --> 00:02:29.680
Capital Pride, the DC
Library Association

00:02:29.680 --> 00:02:32.410
and the Silent Dance Society.

00:02:32.410 --> 00:02:36.060
This program is made possible by
the support of private donations.

00:02:36.060 --> 00:02:39.760
And we invite, and this
is a shameless plug,

00:02:39.760 --> 00:02:42.170
we invite you to join us

00:02:42.170 --> 00:02:48.420
at loc.gov/disco to
make a contribution.

00:02:48.420 --> 00:02:52.410
We also are asking you to live
tweet during the events using the

00:02:52.410 --> 00:02:55.990
hashtag LCDisco.

00:02:55.990 --> 00:03:05.440
And now, for the first session, we
are truly honored to have a woman

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:09.160
who helped symbolize
and create something

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:16.300
that we all know just captures
visually what disco was about.

00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:20.550
You've seen Ms. Yolanda Baker on
various news programs recently

00:03:20.550 --> 00:03:22.680
because she is quite a legend.

00:03:22.680 --> 00:03:28.330
She is the only remaining maker of
disco balls in the United States

00:03:28.330 --> 00:03:34.020
through the Louisville based
Omega National Products.

00:03:34.020 --> 00:03:40.840
She has hand crafted mirror
disco balls for almost 50 years.

00:03:40.840 --> 00:03:43.010
I think that deserves a hand.

00:03:43.010 --> 00:03:44.430
[ Applause ]

00:03:44.430 --> 00:03:47.330
Have you seen my earrings?

00:03:47.330 --> 00:03:49.650
[ Applause ]

00:03:49.650 --> 00:03:54.270
Yolanda's disco balls have been
all over the world including

00:03:54.270 --> 00:04:00.770
at the legendary Club 54 and onset
of the film "Saturday Night Fever"

00:04:00.770 --> 00:04:03.530
which celebrates its 40th
anniversary these years,

00:04:03.530 --> 00:04:09.480
and happens to be in the Library of
Congress's National Film Registry.

00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:14.480
We are especially appreciative of
her participating in this symposium

00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:19.070
on a day that probably is
very important in the world

00:04:19.070 --> 00:04:24.200
of Louisville, Kentucky
native, the Kentucky Derby.

00:04:24.200 --> 00:04:29.080
We are also pleased to have
joining us Toni Lehring

00:04:29.080 --> 00:04:31.170
with the Omega National Products

00:04:31.170 --> 00:04:34.490
where she is the mirror
sales and service manager.

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:37.620
She has worked with
the company since 1994,

00:04:37.620 --> 00:04:40.660
and will share some tidbits
with us about the history

00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:43.450
of the mirror disco ball.

00:04:43.450 --> 00:04:48.890
And then, Rhona Wolfe Friedman
will moderate our first session.

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:53.240
She is a commissioner on the
District of Columbia Arts--

00:04:53.240 --> 00:04:57.270
Commission on Arts and
Humanities, as well as attorney

00:04:57.270 --> 00:05:00.120
and realtor in Washington DC.

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:03.610
And in addition to holding
degrees in law and philosophy,

00:05:03.610 --> 00:05:06.390
she holds a degree in the
history of decorative arts

00:05:06.390 --> 00:05:09.210
from Smithsonian Parsons
School of Design.

00:05:09.210 --> 00:05:15.510
So let's give them a big Library
of Congress disco welcome.

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:22.280
[ Applause ]

00:05:22.280 --> 00:05:23.580
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much.

00:05:23.580 --> 00:05:25.380
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:05:25.380 --> 00:05:35.080
[ Applause ]

00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:37.160
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Thank you.

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:40.010
Thank you all for being here.

00:05:40.010 --> 00:05:43.030
I'm going to introduce
our illustrious speakers

00:05:43.030 --> 00:05:46.970
and Toni is the mirror
and sales service manager

00:05:46.970 --> 00:05:50.630
in the mirror division of
Omega National Products,

00:05:50.630 --> 00:05:52.850
based in Louisville, Kentucky.

00:05:52.850 --> 00:05:58.350
She's been deployed there for
23 years, starting in 1994.

00:05:58.350 --> 00:06:03.020
Omega is the premier manufacture
of wood cabinet accessories,

00:06:03.020 --> 00:06:06.540
as well as architectural
mirrored products.

00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:10.500
These include disco balls
and antique mirrors.

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:13.570
Ms. Lehring is a family
person who loves cooking,

00:06:13.570 --> 00:06:15.950
hiking, camping, and reading.

00:06:15.950 --> 00:06:20.240
She's an avid fan of the
University of Louisville sports.

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:25.000
She has two daughters and
one delightful grandson.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.940
Yolanda Baker is a
production employee

00:06:27.940 --> 00:06:31.660
in the mirror division of Omega.

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:37.510
Ms. Baker has worked in Omega
for 49 years since 1968.

00:06:37.510 --> 00:06:41.140
[ Applause ]

00:06:41.140 --> 00:06:47.130 position:56%
She's an expert in the manufacturing
of mirrored disco balls.

00:06:47.130 --> 00:06:51.700
She also does quality control
for handcrafted mirrors.

00:06:51.700 --> 00:06:56.510
She's been married 51 years to
her husband Tom and has one--

00:06:56.510 --> 00:07:01.290
[ Applause ]

00:07:01.290 --> 00:07:04.310
One married son and two
wonderful grandchildren.

00:07:04.310 --> 00:07:08.390
She enjoys family dinners,
camping, and vacationing.

00:07:08.390 --> 00:07:11.350
Thank you again for
being here on derby day.

00:07:11.350 --> 00:07:15.440
So we're going to start with a
question for either one of you.

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:19.520
Omega National Products make some
of the best mirrors in the world.

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:24.290 position:56%
Can you please give us a little bit
of an explanation about its origins?

00:07:24.290 --> 00:07:25.590
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring: I
can help you with that one.

00:07:25.590 --> 00:07:26.890
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Thank you.

00:07:26.890 --> 00:07:29.800
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring: We've
been making mirror since 1946

00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:31.100
when the company was founded.

00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:34.680
And it was made by
hand, handcrafted.

00:07:34.680 --> 00:07:37.740 position:56%
And at that time, most mirrors were.

00:07:37.740 --> 00:07:42.110
We no longer can use mercury,
but we still have artisans

00:07:42.110 --> 00:07:47.570 position:56%
who can make the handcrafted mirrors
on antique mirror, regular mirror,

00:07:47.570 --> 00:07:52.590
the gold vein mirror, all from like
the art deco histories of furniture

00:07:52.590 --> 00:07:54.980
and furnishings and wall coverings.

00:07:54.980 --> 00:07:59.690 position:56%
And I think the best thing to say is
that because we make it in America,

00:07:59.690 --> 00:08:04.460
because our company is so family
oriented, we just take great pride

00:08:04.460 --> 00:08:06.490
in our work and our craftsmanship.

00:08:06.490 --> 00:08:07.790
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Thank you.

00:08:07.790 --> 00:08:09.090
Thank you.

00:08:09.090 --> 00:08:14.150
Can you explain the tie-in in the
1950s in America to deco furniture

00:08:14.150 --> 00:08:17.240
and mirror and the
desire for everyone

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:20.300
to have their furnitures mirrored?

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:23.470
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring: Well, as
we talked about this before but,

00:08:23.470 --> 00:08:26.940
you know, a lot of the
very wealthy wanted all

00:08:26.940 --> 00:08:29.020
of these replica furniture pieces.

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:30.320
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
That's right.

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:33.390
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring: And then
it was just a lot more affordable

00:08:33.390 --> 00:08:37.820
to have it mirrored, rather
than have the solid woods

00:08:37.820 --> 00:08:41.920
and the exotic woods that
came from other countries.

00:08:41.920 --> 00:08:47.030
And then of course, we've had some
mirrored furniture, the table tops

00:08:47.030 --> 00:08:54.680
and the art deco tables,
occasional tables, I've really--

00:08:54.680 --> 00:08:57.000
I'm trying to think,
oh, I'm so sorry.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.850 position:56%
But, you know, but I think everybody
loves to go into their room

00:09:01.850 --> 00:09:05.290
where it looks expanded and
I think that's what always

00:09:05.290 --> 00:09:06.590
when you have a mirrored room.

00:09:06.590 --> 00:09:07.890
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
That's right.

00:09:07.890 --> 00:09:09.190
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring:
And it just sort of--

00:09:09.190 --> 00:09:12.900
the antique mirror sort
of takes away from some

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:16.170
of that mirrored image and
makes a softer look for people

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:18.890
and it's just kind of elegant.

00:09:18.890 --> 00:09:22.550
And I think it shows a richness.

00:09:22.550 --> 00:09:23.850
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Thank you.

00:09:23.850 --> 00:09:26.370
Now, let's get a little bit
into disco balls-- can--

00:09:26.370 --> 00:09:31.140
who wants to explain to us
the origin of the disco ball?

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:32.560
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring: No, no.

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:35.090
She knows, believe me.

00:09:35.090 --> 00:09:37.820 position:56%
It didn't start in Louisville,
Kentucky, I could tell you all that.

00:09:37.820 --> 00:09:39.120
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Right.

00:09:39.120 --> 00:09:41.220
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring: And I
really wish it did, but it didn't.

00:09:41.220 --> 00:09:43.670
And we weren't involved
when it started.

00:09:43.670 --> 00:09:46.860
So it started over in Europe.

00:09:46.860 --> 00:09:49.680
And, you know, and then it
kind of like, in the '20s,

00:09:49.680 --> 00:09:55.190
you can see disco balls in
old photographs of, you know,

00:09:55.190 --> 00:09:58.630
[inaudible] and ballrooms and,
you know, kind of incorporating

00:09:58.630 --> 00:10:03.040
with the chandeliers and all these
grand ballrooms in Great Britain.

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:07.970
And then of course it came over
into America in the early '20s.

00:10:07.970 --> 00:10:13.020
But we didn't start actually
manufacturing those until the '60s.

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:14.780
We were making a flexible
wall covering

00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:17.170 position:56%
and then a flexible mirror covering.

00:10:17.170 --> 00:10:19.110
And that's what Yolanda does.

00:10:19.110 --> 00:10:21.980
And so then a company
approached us and asked us

00:10:21.980 --> 00:10:28.560
if we would cover various sizes and
shapes of spheres or unique shapes,

00:10:28.560 --> 00:10:30.190
different kinds of substrates.

00:10:30.190 --> 00:10:34.070
And that's when we started
making those around 1960.

00:10:34.070 --> 00:10:36.430
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
What was the largest size

00:10:36.430 --> 00:10:38.270
of a disco ball you've ever made?

00:10:38.270 --> 00:10:41.460
It's also, what is the
oddest one you've ever made?

00:10:41.460 --> 00:10:44.420
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker:
Well, I did a 10 foot.

00:10:44.420 --> 00:10:46.360
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: I'm sorry.

00:10:46.360 --> 00:10:50.310
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker: I did
a 10-foot ball for Coca-Cola.

00:10:50.310 --> 00:10:51.610
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: OK.

00:10:51.610 --> 00:10:52.910
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker:

00:10:52.910 --> 00:10:54.210
And the oddest thing I
covered would be a saddle.

00:10:54.210 --> 00:10:58.100
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring:
Four foot shoe.

00:10:58.100 --> 00:10:59.590
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker: And
a four foot shoe, high heel.

00:10:59.590 --> 00:11:00.890
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring:
A four foot pump.

00:11:00.890 --> 00:11:02.190
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker: High heel.

00:11:02.190 --> 00:11:03.490
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
How did you cover a saddle,

00:11:03.490 --> 00:11:04.790
did someone actually sit on that?

00:11:04.790 --> 00:11:06.090
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker:
I think it was

00:11:06.090 --> 00:11:09.140
for a display, you know, in a bar.

00:11:09.140 --> 00:11:11.640
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Wow.

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:16.000
Can you talk a little bit about
the origins of the disco ball

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.750
in your company, how you
started getting into making them?

00:11:19.750 --> 00:11:22.260
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring: Well, again,
the company that approached us,

00:11:22.260 --> 00:11:25.830
and unfortunately I don't have that
information, but they approached us

00:11:25.830 --> 00:11:30.660
because we were making-- taking
two foot by two foot glass sheets.

00:11:30.660 --> 00:11:31.960
We would silver them.

00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:35.320
We would put a cloth back
and the glass is scored.

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:40.820
And so when we started doing that
for wall coverings like cylinders

00:11:40.820 --> 00:11:44.800
and different curved walls, that's
when the company was approached.

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:49.000
We were making waste baskets,
like we do all accessories,

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:51.730
bathroom accessories, and then
that's when the company came by

00:11:51.730 --> 00:11:55.510
and said, we'd like for
you all to mass produce.

00:11:55.510 --> 00:11:59.390
And at that time, there were
three people in the department,

00:11:59.390 --> 00:12:02.730
one person covering balls,
one person making the shells,

00:12:02.730 --> 00:12:04.690
one person scoring the glass.

00:12:04.690 --> 00:12:08.630
And those three people
grew into 28 people

00:12:08.630 --> 00:12:11.950
within about five years
making an average

00:12:11.950 --> 00:12:15.720
of 25 balls per person per day.

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:21.360
So at that time, we really became
the most revered in America

00:12:21.360 --> 00:12:23.610
as far as making disco balls.

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:27.210
And they went global, I
mean, no pun intended.

00:12:27.210 --> 00:12:31.990
And if you'll notice,
we make mirrored globes

00:12:31.990 --> 00:12:35.960
because disco balls were
called disco balls until disco.

00:12:35.960 --> 00:12:39.210
So, yeah, and we still call
them mirrored globes today.

00:12:39.210 --> 00:12:42.340
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Do you
still make furniture well now

00:12:42.340 --> 00:12:44.640 position:56%
and antique mirrors and disco balls?

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:45.940
What are you doing currently?

00:12:45.940 --> 00:12:47.240
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring: Yeah.

00:12:47.240 --> 00:12:48.540
We don't make the mirrored
furniture.

00:12:48.540 --> 00:12:51.390
We actually make the glass
and mirror and then sell it

00:12:51.390 --> 00:12:54.530
through distribution, sell
it through cabinet companies.

00:12:54.530 --> 00:12:58.100
I actually have a disco
ball desk and credenza,

00:12:58.100 --> 00:13:00.740
and occasional table in my office.

00:13:00.740 --> 00:13:04.660
So I love it so, you know, I said
you all can't throw that away.

00:13:04.660 --> 00:13:10.270
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Can you
describe how you make a disco ball?

00:13:10.270 --> 00:13:11.920
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker:
Well, you have a sphere.

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:13.500
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
Of what, made of?

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:14.800
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker:
It's aluminum.

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:16.100
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: OK.

00:13:16.100 --> 00:13:17.400
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker:
Aluminum shell.

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:18.810
It's hollow on the inside.

00:13:18.810 --> 00:13:23.710
It has a hook on one end
to-- for the hanging.

00:13:23.710 --> 00:13:26.680
You take a belly band
is what I call it.

00:13:26.680 --> 00:13:30.990
So, a strip of glass and you
put it around the middle.

00:13:30.990 --> 00:13:34.200
It's glued on there and you put
glue on the rest of the ball

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:36.380
and you proceed to go up the bulb.

00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:39.520
And it's that simple.

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:42.720
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
Simple she says.

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:47.230
And how long does it take you
to make one of these balls?

00:13:47.230 --> 00:14:02.270
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker: Let's
see, a 12-inch would probably take

00:14:02.270 --> 00:14:07.340
about 15 minutes, that's
a 12-inch in diameter.

00:14:07.340 --> 00:14:08.640
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Wow.

00:14:08.640 --> 00:14:09.940
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker: Yeah.

00:14:09.940 --> 00:14:11.240
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: How--

00:14:11.240 --> 00:14:15.320
what was the longest time it
took you to make one these balls?

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:16.620
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker:
The 10 footer was

00:14:16.620 --> 00:14:19.080
like two or three days, yeah.

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:20.380
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Wow.

00:14:20.380 --> 00:14:21.680
&gt;&gt; Yolanda Ayers Baker: Yeah.

00:14:21.680 --> 00:14:22.980
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Wow.

00:14:22.980 --> 00:14:25.930
Can you talk a little bit about
the trends in the decorative arts

00:14:25.930 --> 00:14:33.080
in the '70s and '80s and how the
balls were involved in culture?

00:14:33.080 --> 00:14:34.380 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring: I think a lot

00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:39.090
of people here could
probably tell us the same,

00:14:39.090 --> 00:14:43.310
if you can remember
like, I can remember

00:14:43.310 --> 00:14:46.770 position:56%
in the '70s, like you can remember--

00:14:46.770 --> 00:14:48.070
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman: Yeah.

00:14:48.070 --> 00:14:50.190
&gt;&gt; Toni Grady Lehring: --
we've had customers come

00:14:50.190 --> 00:14:55.790
in even before my time
there at the company.

