00:34:59.400 --> 00:35:01.160
but let's go to the music.

00:35:01.160 --> 00:35:03.570
What's going on in the music?

00:35:03.570 --> 00:35:06.450
And here, I want to just draw
attention to the fact that a couple

00:35:06.450 --> 00:35:11.060
of days ago, I gave in a talk about
the way in which American music

00:35:11.060 --> 00:35:15.510
from punk and soul-- funk and
soul to Motown disco and so

00:35:15.510 --> 00:35:19.600
on is often derived in large
measure from African music,

00:35:19.600 --> 00:35:23.500
both by way of African-American
music and also particularly by way

00:35:23.500 --> 00:35:26.200
of the Afro-Caribbean influence.

00:35:26.200 --> 00:35:28.120
And today, I want to
tell that kind of story

00:35:28.120 --> 00:35:31.830
which we might call a biography
of musical fragments and patterns

00:35:31.830 --> 00:35:35.530
or what my colleague [inaudible]
and I would call the social life

00:35:35.530 --> 00:35:40.000
of a sound by looking at some of
the details of Beyonce's song.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:45.510
Let's start with that
syncopated bell pattern that--

00:35:45.510 --> 00:35:48.140
[ Tapping ]

00:35:48.140 --> 00:35:50.420
OK, where does that come from?

00:35:50.420 --> 00:35:53.850
It's a kind of a block party
invitation, a summons to come

00:35:53.850 --> 00:35:57.390
to an event and then it has
that strange synthesized vocoder

00:35:57.390 --> 00:36:01.330
like cartoon voice above it,
kind of Mickey Mousing it.

00:36:01.330 --> 00:36:05.760
And as the music enters, it
sort of erupts into a kind

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:08.070
of supreme being energized
by the rhythm.

00:36:08.070 --> 00:36:10.530
Beyonce is suddenly
is alive and almost

00:36:10.530 --> 00:36:15.680
in pantheistic manner also
drawing on a standard cabaret move.

00:36:15.680 --> 00:36:20.020
But the track itself comes from
Major Lazer's track "Pon de Floor"

00:36:20.020 --> 00:36:24.540
from an album called Guns
Don't Kill People, Lazers Do.

00:36:24.540 --> 00:36:26.000
Major Lazer was working

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:29.410
in a Jamaican dance hall
tradition at this point.

00:36:29.410 --> 00:36:36.240
He's a white DJ from Florida by the
name of Wesley Pence and he is--

00:36:36.240 --> 00:36:39.550
he was first-- sort of became
more popularized on mainstream,

00:36:39.550 --> 00:36:43.230
one might say, when he wrote Paper
Planes for MIA which was that--

00:36:43.230 --> 00:36:45.730
this kind of soundtrack
to "Slumdog Millionaire".

00:36:45.730 --> 00:36:49.170
At any rate, this had been
circulating quite widely in Jamaica

00:36:49.170 --> 00:36:55.430
in 2009 and 2010 before
Beyonce decided to use it

00:36:55.430 --> 00:36:58.330
as the central track for
"Girls Run the World".

00:36:58.330 --> 00:37:01.930
So it is already, as I say,
widely circling, circulating.

00:37:01.930 --> 00:37:04.720
Let me give you some example
of how it was circulating.

00:37:04.720 --> 00:37:10.510
Here is Busy Signals' rendition or
version of it called [inaudible].

00:37:10.510 --> 00:37:31.360
[ Music ]

00:37:31.360 --> 00:37:33.740
OK, I'm sorry to cut it
off like that but we need

00:37:33.740 --> 00:37:37.240
to try cover a bit more
ground than one once do.

00:37:37.240 --> 00:37:41.530
But this is directly related
to or the typical sound

00:37:41.530 --> 00:37:43.740 position:56%
of Jamaican dab and dancehall music.

00:37:43.740 --> 00:37:45.390
What is sometimes called versioning

00:37:45.390 --> 00:37:50.580
or what my colleague Michael
Veal calls the aesthetics

00:37:50.580 --> 00:37:53.500
of accumulation or
the rhythm method.

00:37:53.500 --> 00:37:55.750
In this way there's a kind
of audio MIMO [phonetic],

00:37:55.750 --> 00:37:59.510
a dance track that circulates
amongst different DJs and producers

00:37:59.510 --> 00:38:03.970 position:56%
and they repurpose that in different
context and toast over it or wrap

00:38:03.970 --> 00:38:06.760
over it in different ways.

00:38:06.760 --> 00:38:09.780
The tradition of repurposing
existing technology,

00:38:09.780 --> 00:38:13.640
whether it's the turntable in
hip hop or mixing discs and so

00:38:13.640 --> 00:38:18.420 position:56%
on had a long legacy also in Jamaica
and is part of the dancehall scene.

00:38:18.420 --> 00:38:23.250
I want to, however, push that even
further to 19th century Surinam.

00:38:23.250 --> 00:38:26.520
Because if we listen closely
to the track, it was also--

00:38:26.520 --> 00:38:29.250
had a very powerful
snare drum influence

00:38:29.250 --> 00:38:31.900
and that snare drum influence
was probably mediated

00:38:31.900 --> 00:38:36.890
by a DJ called Afrojack who was
the co-producer on the track

00:38:36.890 --> 00:38:40.560
and he was drawing on a regional
dance style from Surinam.

00:38:40.560 --> 00:38:43.750
In Surinam, this particular
dance style known as Kaseko

00:38:43.750 --> 00:38:47.310
or Kaseko is played at
45 beats per minute.

00:38:47.310 --> 00:38:50.540
In other words, just a little bit
faster than Jamaican dancehall

00:38:50.540 --> 00:38:52.970
and itself draws on the tradition,

00:38:52.970 --> 00:38:56.790
the kind of calypso-like style
inflected with marching rhythms

00:38:56.790 --> 00:38:59.690
from the colonial time in Surinam.

00:38:59.690 --> 00:39:04.410
This is interesting because during
this time you have black bands

00:39:04.410 --> 00:39:09.220 position:56%
playing in military-- black
performers playing in military bands

00:39:09.220 --> 00:39:11.860
as part of the colonial regime
but they shift the cadences

00:39:11.860 --> 00:39:15.820
of that European canon in a way to
reflect their own musicalization.

00:39:15.820 --> 00:39:17.560
That's where the syncopations
come in,

00:39:17.560 --> 00:39:19.780
the creolization we might call it.

00:39:19.780 --> 00:39:22.620
Here is a typical track
of this babbling music.

00:39:22.620 --> 00:39:27.360
Babbling is the sort of DJ version
of this older calypso Kaseko style,

00:39:27.360 --> 00:39:32.510
and this is DJ Chuckie, probably
one of the most prominent DJs.

00:39:32.510 --> 00:39:50.730
[ Music ]

00:39:50.730 --> 00:39:53.720
Now, let's go to Johannesburg
in South Africa.

00:39:53.720 --> 00:39:55.240
Here, I'm going to
show you a short clip

00:39:55.240 --> 00:39:58.800
of a dance troupe called Real
Actions, part of what is known

00:39:58.800 --> 00:40:01.450
as the pantsula scene
in South Africa.

00:40:01.450 --> 00:40:05.040
In this case this is probably
our most important pantsula group

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:06.340
at the moment.

00:40:06.340 --> 00:40:07.640
I'll tell you more about them.

00:40:07.640 --> 00:40:09.440
Let's watch how they move.

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:22.030
[ Drumbeat ]

00:40:22.030 --> 00:40:24.040
[ Whistling ]

00:40:24.040 --> 00:40:30.580
OK. As you see, this is quite
virtuosic, low stepping but quick,

00:40:30.580 --> 00:40:34.700
low to the ground kind of urban
street culture that has its origins

00:40:34.700 --> 00:40:38.340
in South African townships and
draws heavily from the mbaqanga

00:40:38.340 --> 00:40:41.110
and marabi musical traditions.

00:40:41.110 --> 00:40:43.480
Quick darting steps,
geometric lines,

00:40:43.480 --> 00:40:45.800
uneven rhythmic quality and so on.

00:40:45.800 --> 00:40:49.460
The word pantsula itself actually
means to waddle like a duck.

00:40:49.460 --> 00:40:52.590
And if you try to move like a
duck you will find yourself moving

00:40:52.590 --> 00:40:56.510 position:56%
like a pantsula, a sort of
flat-footed we might say African tap

00:40:56.510 --> 00:41:00.770
and glide style often
with the buttocks out.

00:41:00.770 --> 00:41:05.250 position:56%
Other dance moves often also follow
the sort of metaphors of daily life.

00:41:05.250 --> 00:41:10.440 position:56%
There's one called [inaudible] which
means like putting butter on bread.

00:41:10.440 --> 00:41:16.030
Now, Beyonce's choreography by
Frank Gatson officially drew

00:41:16.030 --> 00:41:17.360
on this pantsula tradition.

00:41:17.360 --> 00:41:20.030
But she actually didn't work
with Real Actions, instead,

00:41:20.030 --> 00:41:22.240
she went across the
border to Mozambique

00:41:22.240 --> 00:41:24.390
to another troupe called Tofo Tofo.

00:41:24.390 --> 00:41:28.050
Tofo Tofo means or tofo
means shaking the body.

00:41:28.050 --> 00:41:32.000
This is another derivation of
what Real Actions are doing,

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:35.120
and in some ways looked
down upon by Real Actions

00:41:35.120 --> 00:41:39.320
as being derivative itself of
like the real pantsula back home.

00:41:39.320 --> 00:41:43.730
Here is the connection between what
Beyonce found on a YouTube clip,

00:41:43.730 --> 00:41:47.320
the Tofo Tofo performance and
then the relationship that took--

00:41:47.320 --> 00:41:50.510
takes to the choreography
in the video.

00:41:50.510 --> 00:41:56.240
[ Music ]

00:41:56.240 --> 00:41:58.350
[Background Music] This is actually
a slightly different reference,

00:41:58.350 --> 00:42:03.510
but we will get to the one
