00:42:03.510 --> 00:43:00.240
[ Music ]

00:43:00.240 --> 00:43:02.750
OK. I'm, again, cutting
it a little short.

00:43:02.750 --> 00:43:05.030
One can go into this
in much more detail.

00:43:05.030 --> 00:43:07.880
But I would just want to draw
your attention to one small detail

00:43:07.880 --> 00:43:10.790
of the dance in that
that in pantsula dancing,

00:43:10.790 --> 00:43:12.680
there's many different styles.

00:43:12.680 --> 00:43:14.210
And some are called western style,

00:43:14.210 --> 00:43:15.990
the slow poison, there's
[inaudible].

00:43:15.990 --> 00:43:19.870
And what they're doing is
dancing a little bit more

00:43:19.870 --> 00:43:21.910
of the [inaudible] style,
which means your arms are kind

00:43:21.910 --> 00:43:26.140
of wrapped quite tightly around
the torso while the feet do a lot

00:43:26.140 --> 00:43:27.440
of moving.

00:43:27.440 --> 00:43:30.450
It was this that was tricky
for Frank Gatson to work with.

00:43:30.450 --> 00:43:33.910
And Beyonce had the singers
actually flown out to LA

00:43:33.910 --> 00:43:37.820
to choreograph the official dancers
because they couldn't quite get

00:43:37.820 --> 00:43:40.540
that relaxed feeling together.

00:43:40.540 --> 00:43:44.520
Of course, Real Actions were
not that happy about this.

00:43:44.520 --> 00:43:46.310
They thought that Tofo Tofo had

00:43:46.310 --> 00:43:48.820
in some sense brought
their culture down.

00:43:48.820 --> 00:43:50.890
That this was not the
original pantsula,

00:43:50.890 --> 00:43:52.910
that they humiliated
us, I'm quoting.

00:43:52.910 --> 00:43:55.810
Well, at the same time they did
express a certain kind of pride

00:43:55.810 --> 00:44:00.280
in the active recognition from
someone as great as Beyonce.

00:44:00.280 --> 00:44:03.470 position:56%
But, now, I just want to briefly
make one more detour through Africa,

00:44:03.470 --> 00:44:05.280 position:56%
and that is, what about the imagery?

00:44:05.280 --> 00:44:08.940
What about those visuals, the
bull, the hyena, and the lion?

00:44:08.940 --> 00:44:10.500
Where did they come from?

00:44:10.500 --> 00:44:15.120
Particularly this quite striking
scene from Tbilisi on the sign

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:17.380
which is unfortunately
hidden behind the chain

00:44:17.380 --> 00:44:20.690
in her right hand is the sign
to Tbilisi which is the capital

00:44:20.690 --> 00:44:25.170 position:56%
of Georgia which at that time was
not uncontroversial because it was--

00:44:25.170 --> 00:44:27.110
the Israelis had just
closed down the embassy

00:44:27.110 --> 00:44:28.780
in that region and so on.

00:44:28.780 --> 00:44:31.500
But these hyenas on the
chain, these are interesting.

00:44:31.500 --> 00:44:33.390
What do they call up?

00:44:33.390 --> 00:44:37.100
One might say that there's like
sort of exoticized invocations

00:44:37.100 --> 00:44:38.930
of advertising for, you know,

00:44:38.930 --> 00:44:43.500
colonial European tourism
back in the days of Rudisha.

00:44:43.500 --> 00:44:46.490
And all more positively,
one might say, you know,

00:44:46.490 --> 00:44:50.060 position:56%
maybe it's because hyenas themselves
are deeply matriarchal animals.

00:44:50.060 --> 00:44:51.970
Here is what Kevin
Richardson, a conservationist

00:44:51.970 --> 00:45:06.320
in South Africa has
to say about them.

00:45:06.320 --> 00:45:18.390
&gt;&gt; Well, hyenas are
really interesting animals

00:45:21.260 --> 00:45:28.190
because unlike lions they do
have a restrict hierarchy,

00:45:28.190 --> 00:45:31.020
completely misunderstood,
where everyone thinks

00:45:31.020 --> 00:45:34.800
that they are just smelly and
scoundrels and scavengers.

00:45:34.800 --> 00:45:36.100
They do not smell.

00:45:36.100 --> 00:45:37.400
They're not [inaudible].

00:45:37.400 --> 00:45:38.700
They just think [inaudible]
is in there.

00:45:38.700 --> 00:45:42.140
Lowest ranking female ranks higher

00:45:42.140 --> 00:45:45.760
than the highest ranking
male, if that make sense.

00:45:45.760 --> 00:45:49.460
&gt;&gt; But the true reference for these
images is actually the artistic

00:45:49.460 --> 00:45:54.080
photojournalism of Pieter Hugo,
another South African photographer

00:45:54.080 --> 00:46:00.410
who has a particular interest in
photographing marginalized peoples

00:46:00.410 --> 00:46:02.970
around the world, such
as blind people, albinos,

00:46:02.970 --> 00:46:05.800
AIDS victims in their
coffins and so on.

00:46:05.800 --> 00:46:07.410
This is edgy photography.

00:46:07.410 --> 00:46:12.900
And in fact Beyonce is conjuring
that imagery quite strikingly

00:46:12.900 --> 00:46:18.260
in Hugo's hyena and
other men portraits.

00:46:18.260 --> 00:46:23.750 position:56%
The Gadawan Kura, whom you see here,
itinerant minstrels in Nigeria,

00:46:23.750 --> 00:46:28.810
in Abuja, who perform with pet
hyenas and other wild animals,

00:46:28.810 --> 00:46:33.250
baboons, snakes, and so
on to entertain crowds,

00:46:33.250 --> 00:46:36.880
to make music with them,
a kind of miniature circus

00:46:36.880 --> 00:46:38.910
and sell traditional medicines.

00:46:38.910 --> 00:46:40.920
Here are a few more of
these striking images.

00:46:40.920 --> 00:46:42.330
Most interesting about them is

00:46:42.330 --> 00:46:47.210
that in South Africa there's been
a long kind of genealogy or history

00:46:47.210 --> 00:46:52.400
of critical realism in South
African documentary photography

00:46:52.400 --> 00:46:57.120
that dates back to
the Bang Bang Club

00:46:57.120 --> 00:47:00.780
as they were known photographers
who were deeply involved

00:47:00.780 --> 00:47:05.380
with the anti-apartheid
struggle and would go

00:47:05.380 --> 00:47:09.250
into dangerous regions
and take photographs.

00:47:09.250 --> 00:47:10.550
Some got shot.

00:47:10.550 --> 00:47:17.470
Others such as Kevin Carter
actually committed suicide in 1994

00:47:17.470 --> 00:47:20.790
when he won a Pulitzer
Prize for taking an image

00:47:20.790 --> 00:47:23.630
of a starving Ethiopian child
with a circling vulture.

00:47:23.630 --> 00:47:29.320
He found himself also
facing a lot of controversy,

00:47:29.320 --> 00:47:32.740
a few months later he was dead.

00:47:32.740 --> 00:47:39.340
In Hugo's words, what he's trying
to do is problematize the very way

00:47:39.340 --> 00:47:41.310
in which one captures images.

00:47:41.310 --> 00:47:45.040
He says, I am other generation
that approaches photography

00:47:45.040 --> 00:47:48.140
with a keen awareness
of the problems inherent

00:47:48.140 --> 00:47:50.790
in pointing the camera at anything.

00:47:50.790 --> 00:47:52.680
And just to be clear, a
year before the release

00:47:52.680 --> 00:47:56.430
of "Girls Run the World", there
was an exhibition called Permanent

00:47:56.430 --> 00:48:01.630
Error, 2009 to 2010, which was
driving home the darkest side

00:48:01.630 --> 00:48:04.730
of his portraiture and looking at a
place called Agbogbloshie and Ghana

00:48:04.730 --> 00:48:07.510
where he was looking at
the way in which digitalia,

00:48:07.510 --> 00:48:09.970
our digital debris
circulates in the world.

00:48:09.970 --> 00:48:15.350
One of the deep sadnesses of the
history of digital life spans is

00:48:15.350 --> 00:48:18.910
that they begin Africa through
extraction of cassiterite

00:48:18.910 --> 00:48:22.870
and columbite-tantalite in
the Congo and so on often

00:48:22.870 --> 00:48:26.240
under severe conditions and
then find their way back

00:48:26.240 --> 00:48:28.470
when we dump our waste
back in Africa.

00:48:28.470 --> 00:48:31.880
And here you see the
Agbogbloshie toxic waste dump site

00:48:31.880 --> 00:48:36.150 position:56%
where people are trying to extract a
living out of this misguided policy

00:48:36.150 --> 00:48:37.450
of shipping millions of tons

00:48:37.450 --> 00:48:38.750
of obsolete materials
in that direction.

00:48:38.750 --> 00:48:40.050 position:56%
Pieter Hugo's response when he was--

00:48:40.050 --> 00:48:41.350
when it was raised that this was
what Beyonce was referencing said,

00:48:41.350 --> 00:48:42.650
you know, he was not sure if
it fitted really into the song

00:48:42.650 --> 00:48:43.950
but that he did feel that perhaps
the hyena men might be looking

00:48:43.950 --> 00:48:45.450
for compensation for some of
their efforts in that production.

00:48:45.450 --> 00:48:46.980
I want to make one final
point before closing for today

00:48:46.980 --> 00:48:48.280 position:56%
because it's a purely musical point.

00:48:48.280 --> 00:48:49.680
We spoke about a little bit about
the way in which the snare drums

00:48:49.680 --> 00:48:50.980
that have been brought

00:48:50.980 --> 00:48:52.280
in were referencing this
calypso style, Kaseko and so on.

00:48:52.280 --> 00:48:53.580
We had gotten to the
Afro-Caribbean world.

00:48:53.580 --> 00:48:54.880
What's often forgotten in
accounts that you find on Wikipedia

00:48:54.880 --> 00:48:56.180
or in the bloggers
[inaudible] or in the, you know,

00:48:56.180 --> 00:48:57.480
the large scale media
is the next step.

00:48:57.480 --> 00:48:58.780
Where did that come from?

00:48:58.780 --> 00:49:00.080
And I wanted to draw
attention these clave patterns

00:49:00.080 --> 00:49:01.380
that are being drawn on,

00:49:01.380 --> 00:49:02.680
that striking pattern
that goes like this.

00:49:02.680 --> 00:49:03.980
[ Tapping ]

00:49:03.980 --> 00:49:06.170
The forward clave pattern which
if I would have put a beat

00:49:06.170 --> 00:49:08.350
to it would be something like this.

00:49:08.350 --> 00:49:10.690
[ Tapping ]

00:49:10.690 --> 00:49:15.930
OK? That is very strikingly
if you speed up the--

00:49:15.930 --> 00:49:20.510
that pattern a little bit you
get precisely that opening track.

00:49:20.510 --> 00:49:36.400
[ Music ]

00:49:36.400 --> 00:49:39.120
OK. Now where does
that sound come from?

00:49:39.120 --> 00:49:40.510
We know it as being this--

00:49:40.510 --> 00:49:44.210
associated with this
on a clave pattern,

00:49:44.210 --> 00:49:48.290
but I want to return it back to
its origins, which is in Africa.

00:49:48.290 --> 00:49:50.140
And the way you feel that pattern

00:49:50.140 --> 00:49:52.030
in Africa is just a
little bit different.

00:49:52.030 --> 00:49:53.330
Instead of--

00:49:53.330 --> 00:49:54.920
[ Tapping ]

00:49:54.920 --> 00:49:56.720
-- you play it this way.

00:49:56.720 --> 00:50:01.550
[ Tapping ]

00:50:01.550 --> 00:50:04.870
Now you will hear in some ways all
I'm doing is playing a pattern a

00:50:04.870 --> 00:50:06.490
little bit more slowly.

00:50:06.490 --> 00:50:10.010
But in fact I'm playing
it in a different pulse.

00:50:10.010 --> 00:50:12.510
So if I'm playing this
one and it's going--

00:50:12.510 --> 00:50:15.990
[ Tapping ]

00:50:15.990 --> 00:50:17.790
And the other one--

00:50:17.790 --> 00:50:20.360
[ Tapping ]

00:50:20.360 --> 00:50:24.610
The one is going [tapping table]
one, two, one, two, one, two, one,

00:50:24.610 --> 00:50:26.990
two and the other one, one, two,
three, one, two, three, one,

00:50:26.990 --> 00:50:28.790
two, three, one, two, three.

00:50:28.790 --> 00:50:33.070
[ Tapping ]

00:50:33.070 --> 00:50:35.570
One, two, three, one, two, three,
one, two, three, one, two, three.

00:50:35.570 --> 00:50:39.850
And it's this change or the
transformation of ternary time,

00:50:39.850 --> 00:50:42.730
we call it, in threes,
to binary time that I'd

00:50:42.730 --> 00:50:46.380
like to note in my closing remarks.

00:50:46.380 --> 00:50:48.160
Where does this pattern come from?

00:50:48.160 --> 00:50:52.060 position:56%
It's hard to find a region in
Africa where it doesn't play a role.

00:50:52.060 --> 00:50:56.640
But I'm just going to play you
one of the typical bell patterns

00:50:56.640 --> 00:50:58.400
that is associated with gankogui

00:50:58.400 --> 00:51:03.540
which is a bell instrument
with two tones.

00:51:03.540 --> 00:51:08.030 position:56%
And it's part of an ensemble usually
such as agbekor or [inaudible].

00:51:08.030 --> 00:51:10.760
And here's the way in slow motion

00:51:10.760 --> 00:51:13.510
that that particular
bell pattern sounds.

00:51:13.510 --> 00:51:22.130
[ Music ]

00:51:22.130 --> 00:51:25.350
Seven strokes before
it begins again.

00:51:25.350 --> 00:51:29.200
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven, one.

00:51:29.200 --> 00:51:37.290
OK. If I play a second part
and I'm just going to have

00:51:37.290 --> 00:51:38.790
to demonstrate this quickly.

00:51:38.790 --> 00:51:40.590
Here is the bell pattern.

00:51:40.590 --> 00:51:43.520
[ Tapping ]

00:51:43.520 --> 00:51:45.240
And I'll play all the
spaces in between

00:51:45.240 --> 00:51:48.510
that which is what your rattle
player in this ensemble will do.

00:51:48.510 --> 00:51:57.280
[ Rattle Sound ]

00:51:57.280 --> 00:52:01.580
That is what will become the
clave pattern as it crosses

00:52:01.580 --> 00:52:03.810
over into the Afro-Caribbean.

00:52:03.810 --> 00:52:08.860 position:56%
OK. So it's within the sort of
rattling of this particular ensemble

00:52:08.860 --> 00:52:11.590 position:56%
that that clave pattern is embedded.

00:52:11.590 --> 00:52:15.880
One way in which we find a
transformation taking place is

00:52:15.880 --> 00:52:19.290
that instead of hearing that in
ternary time, as said we hear it

00:52:19.290 --> 00:52:23.470 position:56%
in binary time, but what is striking
about the African version is

00:52:23.470 --> 00:52:27.420
that you can hear that
pattern in any of many ways.

00:52:27.420 --> 00:52:29.730
So if I play you that pattern
again, I'm going to beat

00:52:29.730 --> 00:52:33.510
out different "drumbeats"
against it.

00:52:33.510 --> 00:52:43.310
[ Tapping ]

00:52:43.310 --> 00:52:45.110
Or--

00:52:45.110 --> 00:52:48.800
[ Tapping ]

00:52:48.800 --> 00:52:50.600
Or--

00:52:50.600 --> 00:52:54.410
[ Tapping ]

00:52:54.410 --> 00:52:56.210
Or--

00:52:56.210 --> 00:53:01.020
[ Tapping ]

00:53:01.020 --> 00:53:04.580
OK. What's interesting about it is
that it's organized in such a way,

00:53:04.580 --> 00:53:06.640
for those of you that can
read [inaudible] theory,

00:53:06.640 --> 00:53:09.750
that it can entrain
our bodies in any

00:53:09.750 --> 00:53:13.810
of many different time
signatures at the same time.

00:53:13.810 --> 00:53:18.160
The structure of it is long, long,
short, long, long, long, short.

00:53:18.160 --> 00:53:21.370
A little bit like the structure
of the white notes on a piano

00:53:21.370 --> 00:53:25.670
where you have a tone, tone, half
tone, tone, tone, tone, half tone.

00:53:25.670 --> 00:53:29.360
And it is that ambiguity, that
possibility for entraining the body

00:53:29.360 --> 00:53:33.400
in many different ways that is
in some sense lost when it moves

00:53:33.400 --> 00:53:36.560
over into the Afro-Caribbean
and become something

00:53:36.560 --> 00:53:39.990
that is a little more shoe
horned into binary time.

00:53:39.990 --> 00:53:44.900 position:56%
It is that small loss that I want to
register when we look at more depth

00:53:44.900 --> 00:53:49.490
into what these-- what's at stake
globally into all these musics

00:53:49.490 --> 00:53:53.010
that take us in some--
sometimes to some sad places

00:53:53.010 --> 00:53:57.010
such as the toxic waste
dumpsite in Agbogbloshie and also

00:53:57.010 --> 00:53:59.640
into a time signature
that it's a little less

00:53:59.640 --> 00:54:01.460
than what it was in its origin.

00:54:01.460 --> 00:54:03.510
OK, thank you very much.

00:54:03.510 --> 00:54:14.500
