00:55:25.050 --> 00:55:34.570
I want to just talk about my
experience with the disco culture.

00:55:34.570 --> 00:55:43.610
I photographed disco
from 1977 to 1979.

00:55:43.610 --> 00:55:47.240
And I was thrown into this culture.

00:55:47.240 --> 00:55:49.500
I'll give you a little
background about myself.

00:55:49.500 --> 00:55:51.980
I was born in the '50s.

00:55:51.980 --> 00:55:56.570
I was one of the Woodstock
generation.

00:55:56.570 --> 00:56:00.800
The first big cultural phenomenon
that I remember as a kid was

00:56:00.800 --> 00:56:05.670
when The Beatles came over to
America on the Ed Sullivan Show.

00:56:05.670 --> 00:56:09.420
And that for me kind
of changed everything.

00:56:09.420 --> 00:56:10.990
I became a musician.

00:56:10.990 --> 00:56:14.240
I got a set of Ludwig
Drums and I played

00:56:14.240 --> 00:56:17.210
in a rock band in high school.

00:56:17.210 --> 00:56:25.440
And I guess my culture as a young
man was kind of the hippie culture.

00:56:25.440 --> 00:56:27.270
Although I wasn't a
full fledged hippie

00:56:27.270 --> 00:56:32.110
but that was kind of
where I came from.

00:56:32.110 --> 00:56:35.360
So we were, you know, antiwar.

00:56:35.360 --> 00:56:42.720
We were mostly white,
middle class, long haired,

00:56:42.720 --> 00:56:46.500
suburban, most-- a lot of us.

00:56:46.500 --> 00:56:54.370
I got tear gassed in the mall like
right down the street here in 1970

00:56:54.370 --> 00:56:57.500
when I was protesting the war.

00:56:57.500 --> 00:57:01.100
Anyway, after I got out of college,

00:57:01.100 --> 00:57:04.300
I decided to become a photographer
and this is in the '70s.

00:57:04.300 --> 00:57:11.280
And the first place that would hire
me I guess was the Village Voice

00:57:11.280 --> 00:57:12.580
in New York City.

00:57:12.580 --> 00:57:16.990
And this was in about 1976.

00:57:16.990 --> 00:57:23.290
And so I was photographing
a lot of street photography

00:57:23.290 --> 00:57:26.660 position:56%
and portraiture, that kind of thing.

00:57:26.660 --> 00:57:31.380
And one night, I was asked to--
I was assigned to go to Studio 54

00:57:31.380 --> 00:57:38.210
to photograph an awards
presentation for Lillian Carter,

00:57:38.210 --> 00:57:40.810
who is Jimmy Carter,
the president's mother.

00:57:40.810 --> 00:57:44.410
She was being awarded
a humanitarian award.

00:57:44.410 --> 00:57:48.910
And I had never been to Studio
54 before and I had no--

00:57:48.910 --> 00:57:50.720
kind of no interest in going.

00:57:50.720 --> 00:57:56.500
I had a curiosity but I was
not a big fan of disco music.

00:57:56.500 --> 00:58:00.230
And at that time, my rock station

00:58:00.230 --> 00:58:05.310
in New York overnight turned
from rock to all disco.

00:58:05.310 --> 00:58:09.850
And a lot of people were
a little bit confused

00:58:09.850 --> 00:58:12.020
and not happy with that.

00:58:12.020 --> 00:58:16.400
So I was well aware of the
fact that disco was happening.

00:58:16.400 --> 00:58:20.690
And I saw "Saturday Night
Fever" which came out 1977.

00:58:20.690 --> 00:58:24.470
And so it was a phenomenon
that was occurring.

00:58:24.470 --> 00:58:29.590
And I consider my self
a photojournalist,

00:58:29.590 --> 00:58:35.470
a portrait photographer and a
bit of a cultural anthropologist.

00:58:35.470 --> 00:58:40.260
I like to get involved in
different cultures and look at them

00:58:40.260 --> 00:58:45.890
and photograph them and disco
certainly was its own culture.

00:58:45.890 --> 00:58:50.950
So anyway, I was sent to Studio 54

00:58:50.950 --> 00:58:54.950
and this is what it looked
like from the outside.

00:58:54.950 --> 00:58:57.090
It was a very difficult
place to get into.

00:58:57.090 --> 00:58:58.770
It opened up in '77.

00:58:58.770 --> 00:59:02.910
And there was always a-- they
started the velvet rope policy

00:59:02.910 --> 00:59:09.370
where people would stand outside
and be chosen, you know, based on--

00:59:09.370 --> 00:59:13.410
I'm not exactly sure what but
I know a few were a celebrity

00:59:13.410 --> 00:59:16.170
who had a good chance
of getting in but not--

00:59:16.170 --> 00:59:19.130
you didn't always get in
but you had a good chance.

00:59:19.130 --> 00:59:24.340
So this is what I saw the
first night that I got there.

00:59:24.340 --> 00:59:30.870
And when I walked inside,
this is what I encountered.

00:59:30.870 --> 00:59:34.780
And I had never seen
anything like this before.

00:59:34.780 --> 00:59:37.420
I was just, you know,
shooting on the street

00:59:37.420 --> 00:59:39.320
or if I was shooting a portrait,

00:59:39.320 --> 00:59:41.670
I would have the person
pretty much all to myself.

00:59:41.670 --> 00:59:46.870
And so this was, you know, the--

00:59:46.870 --> 00:59:51.980
The word paparazzi was kind
of a new word back in 1977.

00:59:51.980 --> 00:59:54.150
And, you know, here they are.

00:59:54.150 --> 00:59:56.190
They're just like on
top of each other.

00:59:56.190 --> 01:00:02.770
And to me as a photographer,
this was more interesting a shot

01:00:02.770 --> 01:00:05.070
than what they were shooting.

01:00:06.470 --> 01:00:08.050
But that's what they were shooting.

01:00:08.050 --> 01:00:12.080
So that's Lillian Carter and--
sitting next to Andy Warhol.

01:00:12.080 --> 01:00:16.240 position:56%
And that's the shot that the Village
Voice sent me to get which I got.

01:00:16.240 --> 01:00:25.640
And then I decided that after the
event was over that I would stay

01:00:25.640 --> 01:00:32.190
because I didn't know if I
could ever get back in again.

01:00:32.190 --> 01:00:35.880
So, I bought 10 rolls of
film from a photographer

01:00:35.880 --> 01:00:39.860
who is leaving, from
one of those guys.

01:00:39.860 --> 01:00:45.860
And I basically hung out in
the shadows up in the balcony

01:00:45.860 --> 01:00:52.110 position:56%
so I didn't get kick out, and waited
for the regular crowd to come in.

01:00:52.110 --> 01:00:55.130
They put all the tables
away and cleaned up

01:00:55.130 --> 01:00:59.500
and then the regular crowd came in.

01:00:59.500 --> 01:01:04.370
And this is really one of the
very first pictures that I took

01:01:04.370 --> 01:01:08.550
that night in '77, this
was in December of '77.

01:01:08.550 --> 01:01:14.230
Studio 54 had opened I think
about a month or two before that.

01:01:14.230 --> 01:01:21.000
Studio 54 was actually opened
from '77 to '79 which is like--

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:24.360
it was like two and a half
years something like that.

01:01:24.360 --> 01:01:25.940
When I tell people that,
they can't believe it

01:01:25.940 --> 01:01:28.890
because they think it was
opened for like 10 years.

01:01:28.890 --> 01:01:32.300
But it was a very, very short
period of time when it was owned

01:01:32.300 --> 01:01:35.090
by Steve Rubell and Ian Schrager

01:01:35.090 --> 01:01:40.290
who were the original
creators of Studio 54.

01:01:40.290 --> 01:01:43.770
So this is the first
picture that I really took

01:01:43.770 --> 01:01:46.730
after I took the shot
for the Village Voice.

01:01:46.730 --> 01:01:50.610
And as I was taking this
picture, I think I --

01:01:50.610 --> 01:01:53.170
this might be the only
real frame that I got.

01:01:53.170 --> 01:01:56.470
I got a couple of pictures of them
from the back and then I asked them

01:01:56.470 --> 01:01:59.620
if I could shoot them and
then I shot this and then went

01:01:59.620 --> 01:02:00.920
on to shoot something else.

01:02:00.920 --> 01:02:03.840
But it really stuck in my
mind because it reminded me

01:02:03.840 --> 01:02:08.470
of a prewar Berlin Cabaret.

01:02:08.470 --> 01:02:12.760
And I started to think about
that and I remember, you know,

01:02:12.760 --> 01:02:16.210
seeing the movie "Cabaret" and
just, you know, the whole sort

01:02:16.210 --> 01:02:25.320 position:56%
of gender-bending undertone, sort
of gay undertone and sadomasochistic

01:02:25.320 --> 01:02:29.970
and just a lot of things
sort of popped into my mind

01:02:29.970 --> 01:02:32.370
when I photographed this couple.

01:02:32.370 --> 01:02:34.460
And I started looking around.

01:02:34.460 --> 01:02:35.770
This was later that night.

01:02:35.770 --> 01:02:37.520
And I just started to have--

01:02:37.520 --> 01:02:41.080
see these images all around me

01:02:41.080 --> 01:02:47.690
of this prewar Berlin
Cabaret sort of thing.

01:02:47.690 --> 01:02:50.630
This was a group that
was-- they would--

01:02:50.630 --> 01:02:53.820
they came in altogether and they--
through the course of the night,

01:02:53.820 --> 01:02:58.220
they would dance together, the
guys would dance with the guys,

01:02:58.220 --> 01:03:01.160
sometimes the two guys
would sandwich the girl

01:03:01.160 --> 01:03:02.630
on the dance floor.

01:03:02.630 --> 01:03:06.300
I didn't know who was who
or what was what with them,

01:03:06.300 --> 01:03:09.740
but they were like this group that
hang out together and they were

01:03:09.740 --> 01:03:12.000
in this own little bubble.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:16.370
And I just kept an eye out on them
and when they got on the couch

01:03:16.370 --> 01:03:18.480
like this that was across the floor

01:03:18.480 --> 01:03:22.430
and I just thought that's
really an interesting picture.

01:03:22.430 --> 01:03:27.210
So I sort of like hoped I could
get across the floor with my camera

01:03:27.210 --> 01:03:30.560
without them moving, you know,
without them getting up and leaving

01:03:30.560 --> 01:03:33.390
which I did and I walked
over and I snapped a couple

01:03:33.390 --> 01:03:35.510
of shots and that was it.

01:03:35.510 --> 01:03:39.800
And people asked me
if this was posed?

01:03:39.800 --> 01:03:41.780
And it was not posed at all.

01:03:41.780 --> 01:03:44.850
It was-- They were
posing, but not for me.

01:03:44.850 --> 01:03:47.220
I mean they were posing
before I got there.

01:03:47.220 --> 01:03:51.110
And it's like-- almost like
they felt like as I watched them

01:03:51.110 --> 01:03:56.050
that night that they were sort
of the stars of the evening.

01:03:56.050 --> 01:03:59.870
And they had this, you
know, aura about them.

01:03:59.870 --> 01:04:04.220 position:56%
And they were in this little bubble.

01:04:04.220 --> 01:04:08.730
So, I chose at the very beginning
when I went to Studio 54 not

01:04:08.730 --> 01:04:12.830
to photograph celebrities, it
was like an early decision.

01:04:12.830 --> 01:04:17.240
And the reason I did that
was a couple of reasons.

01:04:17.240 --> 01:04:20.880
First of all, everybody was
shooting the celebrities

01:04:20.880 --> 01:04:27.050 position:56%
and that was what photographers
were doing at places like Studio 54.

01:04:27.050 --> 01:04:30.390
And they were all kind
of getting the same shot.

01:04:30.390 --> 01:04:35.260
So I thought, you know, if
I want to shoot a celebrity,

01:04:35.260 --> 01:04:40.160
I want them like in my studio with
my lighting and I want to talk

01:04:40.160 --> 01:04:45.550
to them and, you know, interact
and get a picture, you know,

01:04:45.550 --> 01:04:50.620
get something that I want to get
and not just sort of snap a picture

01:04:50.620 --> 01:04:52.320
of them sitting on a couch.

01:04:52.320 --> 01:04:55.620
So, I decided that I didn't
want to shoot celebrities.

01:04:55.620 --> 01:04:57.980
But I also thought that
what was more interesting

01:04:57.980 --> 01:05:04.460 position:56%
than the celebrities were like the
people who went there and the people

01:05:04.460 --> 01:05:06.640
who like live the disco life.

01:05:06.640 --> 01:05:12.470
And I started to see things also.

01:05:12.470 --> 01:05:16.600
This looks like a transgender woman
with like a sort of a straight--

01:05:16.600 --> 01:05:20.020
Wall Street banger type guy.

01:05:20.020 --> 01:05:24.050
And I started to realize that were
something really interesting going

01:05:24.050 --> 01:05:26.720
on at the disco.

01:05:26.720 --> 01:05:31.320
I wasn't exactly sure what it was,
it wasn't crystal clear in my mind,

01:05:31.320 --> 01:05:34.820
but I felt like there's
something really interesting here

01:05:34.820 --> 01:05:37.300
from a photographic
point of view and just

01:05:37.300 --> 01:05:39.160
from a cultural point of view.

01:05:39.160 --> 01:05:44.360
And what it was, was it was this
freedom of expression, it was this,

01:05:44.360 --> 01:05:46.500
you know, openness, acceptance,

01:05:46.500 --> 01:05:52.030
inclusion that I'd
never seen before.

01:05:52.030 --> 01:05:56.680
And what was happening
was-- move on.

01:05:56.680 --> 01:06:00.940
What was happening is during
the '60s and early '70s,

01:06:00.940 --> 01:06:04.400 position:56%
there was the women's movement,
there was the civil rights movement,

01:06:04.400 --> 01:06:08.400
there was post-Stonewall, you
know, there was the LGBT movement.

01:06:08.400 --> 01:06:13.520
And all of these movements
sort of came together

01:06:13.520 --> 01:06:15.870
at the same time disco happened.

01:06:15.870 --> 01:06:20.510
And the disco was a place for all
of these different movements to go

01:06:20.510 --> 01:06:26.550
and have what one writer
described as a victory dance.

01:06:26.550 --> 01:06:33.130
So, they were all there in unison
having their victory dance.

01:06:33.130 --> 01:06:37.340
And I'd never seen anything
like this, you know.

01:06:37.340 --> 01:06:40.710
You know, again coming from
the Woodstock generation.

01:06:40.710 --> 01:06:44.590
And if you go back and take a
look at the movie "Woodstock",

01:06:44.590 --> 01:06:49.270 position:56%
you can probably count on one hand
how many African Americans there are

01:06:49.270 --> 01:06:50.570
in the audience.

01:06:50.570 --> 01:06:56.380 position:56%
They're all mostly white, long
haired, you know, middle class kids.

01:06:56.380 --> 01:07:01.430
Most of the entertainers were
African American or, you know,

01:07:01.430 --> 01:07:07.090 position:56%
Hispanic, but the audience itself
was not like this kind of inclusion.

01:07:07.090 --> 01:07:13.340
You can see that many transgenders
in the "Woodstock" movie, you know.

01:07:13.340 --> 01:07:17.900
So, this was all completely
new to me.

01:07:17.900 --> 01:07:22.850
It was just-- I was just--
My eyes were, you know,

01:07:22.850 --> 01:07:25.910
bugging out of my head
by what I was seeing.

01:07:25.910 --> 01:07:34.890
It just seemed like a place
of freedom of expression and,

01:07:34.890 --> 01:07:37.470
you know, be who you want to be.

01:07:44.900 --> 01:07:52.640
And it was young, old and this was
a particular interesting character

01:07:52.640 --> 01:07:54.550
name Rollerena.

01:07:54.550 --> 01:08:01.070
And Rollerena had this gown like
it is, you know, and the glasses

01:08:01.070 --> 01:08:06.500
and the hat and this magic
wand and roller skates.

01:08:06.500 --> 01:08:11.270
And he was a fixture
in Greenwich Village.

01:08:11.270 --> 01:08:15.850
You would see him all the time, you
know, out roller skating around,

01:08:15.850 --> 01:08:18.540
and he would bless
you with his wand.

01:08:18.540 --> 01:08:23.580
And he was a fixture
at most of the--

01:08:23.580 --> 01:08:28.100
like Xenon, was one of the
big discos, and Studio 54.

01:08:28.100 --> 01:08:35.220
This is Disco Sally who was
I believe in her mid 70s.

01:08:35.220 --> 01:08:39.160
She was a lawyer and her husband
was a lawyer and her husband died

01:08:39.160 --> 01:08:43.850
and she was left alone and
heartbroken and never been

01:08:43.850 --> 01:08:46.820
to a disco, but some
friend said, come on out,

01:08:46.820 --> 01:08:49.220
let's go, you know, to Studio 54.

01:08:49.220 --> 01:08:51.290
And she went and she
actually loved it

01:08:51.290 --> 01:08:57.600
and she became a regular
at Studio 54 and Xenon.

01:08:57.600 --> 01:09:04.750 position:56%
People used-- Usually young African
Americans or Hispanic muscular guys,

01:09:04.750 --> 01:09:08.100
young guys would-- she'd
wrapped her legs around them

01:09:08.100 --> 01:09:10.510
and they would spin her around.

01:09:10.510 --> 01:09:16.290
[ Laughter ]

01:09:16.290 --> 01:09:20.650
Again this is-- you know, really
just freedom of expression

01:09:20.650 --> 01:09:25.080
and a safe place to
be and a safe haven.

01:09:25.080 --> 01:09:29.990
This is a contact sheet,
and I don't know how--

01:09:29.990 --> 01:09:31.290
I can't really see you people

01:09:31.290 --> 01:09:35.500
but I don't know how many people
know what a contact sheet is.

01:09:35.500 --> 01:09:37.010
Yeah? Good.

01:09:37.010 --> 01:09:38.630
[ Applause ]

01:09:38.630 --> 01:09:40.820
That's heartening to know.

01:09:40.820 --> 01:09:46.120
But when I started shooting,
that's what we had to deal with.

01:09:46.120 --> 01:09:53.450
We-- I would go out at night with
my Canon F-1 and Vivitar 273 flash

01:09:53.450 --> 01:09:57.770
and I would shoot with Tri-X
film which was the fastest film

01:09:57.770 --> 01:10:01.210
of its day, it was 400 ASA.

01:10:01.210 --> 01:10:05.770 position:56%
And I needed fast film because these
clubs were dark, like I'm looking

01:10:05.770 --> 01:10:09.630
out here now, this was-- some
clubs were as dark as this

01:10:09.630 --> 01:10:12.790
but there'll be flashing
lights so I would have a moment

01:10:12.790 --> 01:10:16.370
to focus my camera when
a light flashed on.

01:10:16.370 --> 01:10:18.980
But it was a really
difficult shooting situation

01:10:18.980 --> 01:10:22.490
that took me a long
time to figure out.

01:10:22.490 --> 01:10:26.570
But-- So what I did was when
I was seriously shooting a lot

01:10:26.570 --> 01:10:31.560
for this project, I would go
out sometimes at about four

01:10:31.560 --> 01:10:35.730
in the morning and I come back and
I take my 10, 15 rolls of film,

01:10:35.730 --> 01:10:41.040
I put them on my table and I go
to sleep and I had an assistant

01:10:41.040 --> 01:10:46.110
that would come in about 10 o'clock
in the morning and develop the film

01:10:46.110 --> 01:10:52.240
and hang it up to dry and I would
rise at about four in the afternoon

01:10:52.240 --> 01:10:57.630
and have a really strong
cup of coffee or two and sit

01:10:57.630 --> 01:11:02.470
and I'd make a contact sheet and
I'll sit and look at it and I'd see

01:11:02.470 --> 01:11:04.590
if I got anything the night before.

01:11:04.590 --> 01:11:07.240
Because, you know, it's not like
being able to shoot and look

01:11:07.240 --> 01:11:10.370
at the back of your camera and say,
oh yeah, that's good, you know.

01:11:10.370 --> 01:11:13.700
You had to wait and look
at the contact sheet.

01:11:13.700 --> 01:11:18.000
So that was the process that
I went through to shoot.

01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:22.150
And, you know, honestly,
I don't miss it.

01:11:22.150 --> 01:11:24.280
[ Laughter ]

01:11:24.280 --> 01:11:28.180
Much easier to shoot digitally.

01:11:28.180 --> 01:11:30.610
Another thing at the disco

01:11:30.610 --> 01:11:35.360
in this particular time
period was the evolution

01:11:35.360 --> 01:11:39.110
of the technology of
the sound system.

01:11:39.110 --> 01:11:42.910
You know, if you remember
or you won't remember this,

01:11:42.910 --> 01:11:49.250 position:56%
but when The Beatles played at Shea
Stadium, the sound that they played,

01:11:49.250 --> 01:11:51.100
the speakers that they played

01:11:51.100 --> 01:11:54.500
through were the little
blow horns that, you know,

01:11:54.500 --> 01:11:56.980
they would announce the
next, you know, batter,

01:11:56.980 --> 01:12:00.620
that was the technology of the day.

01:12:00.620 --> 01:12:03.460
Well, this was, you
know, now 10 years later

01:12:03.460 --> 01:12:08.280
and the speaker system was
incredible and, you know,

01:12:08.280 --> 01:12:14.190
the mixing devices and the
amplifiers were very high tech.

01:12:14.190 --> 01:12:20.290
This is a-- This is really the only
female DJ that I've photographed

01:12:20.290 --> 01:12:23.900
or found in New York
City during that period.

01:12:23.900 --> 01:12:29.220 position:56%
And I'm not saying there weren't
others that I didn't find but at one

01:12:29.220 --> 01:12:32.430
of the major discos,
this is the only one,

01:12:32.430 --> 01:12:34.420
this was the place called Sybil's.

01:12:34.420 --> 01:12:39.910
It's pretty much a men's
club and I think it still is

01:12:39.910 --> 01:12:44.000
to some extent today although
I've met some amazing female DJs

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:46.700
in the last few years.

01:12:46.700 --> 01:12:48.830
So, it's-- you know, they're
kind of breaking through.

01:12:48.830 --> 01:12:55.850
This is a-- These are the
speakers, I mean, they're huge.

01:12:55.850 --> 01:13:02.590
And like this is-- this would be
a one sort of set of speakers here

01:13:02.590 --> 01:13:06.770
and in some of the clubs they would
just have these speakers lining

01:13:06.770 --> 01:13:08.840
the wall.

01:13:08.840 --> 01:13:15.250
So, when they played, you know,
that-- you know, the disco beat,

01:13:15.250 --> 01:13:20.260
the base especially, it would
really rock your insides.

01:13:20.260 --> 01:13:24.220
And you would like get
a physical high just--

01:13:24.220 --> 01:13:27.380
even if you had done no drugs
and walked in off the street,

01:13:27.380 --> 01:13:29.490
just if you were standing
in that room for a while,

01:13:29.490 --> 01:13:33.000
you would actually-- your insides
sort to shake and, you know,

01:13:33.000 --> 01:13:35.750
you would get high
just for being there.

01:13:35.750 --> 01:13:40.440
So, you add the drugs and the
alcohol to that and, you know,

01:13:40.440 --> 01:13:44.210
it was a pretty amazing scene.

01:13:44.210 --> 01:13:55.940
So, after Studio 54, I decided that
this is interesting and I wanted

01:13:55.940 --> 01:13:58.070
to see what else was going on.

01:13:58.070 --> 01:14:00.970
And this-- again, this is '77, '78.

01:14:00.970 --> 01:14:06.930 position:56%
I want to see what else was going on
in Manhattan and the five boroughs.

01:14:06.930 --> 01:14:11.790
So, I went to-- this
is 2001 Odyssey where

01:14:11.790 --> 01:14:14.380
"Saturday Night Fever" was filmed.

01:14:14.380 --> 01:14:18.490
And it wasn't exactly the most--
it was in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn

01:14:18.490 --> 01:14:22.190
and it wasn't exactly like
the upscale Manhattan disco,

01:14:22.190 --> 01:14:25.740
it was kind of like a local disco.

01:14:25.740 --> 01:14:31.030
This is the floor that
was in the movie.

01:14:31.030 --> 01:14:33.920
It was actually built
by Robert Stigwood

01:14:33.920 --> 01:14:36.840
and is-- his production people.

01:14:36.840 --> 01:14:42.230
But it stayed in 2001
Odyssey after they left.

01:14:42.230 --> 01:14:45.830
And when the building was
torn down some time later,

01:14:45.830 --> 01:14:49.550
some private collector
bought this floor.

01:14:49.550 --> 01:14:52.740
And I don't know where
it is but somewhere in--

01:14:52.740 --> 01:14:58.900
probably in California, in LA, in
somebody's basement is this floor

01:14:58.900 --> 01:15:02.620
and he has parties on
Saturday night [laughs].

01:15:06.090 --> 01:15:11.550
This was really one of the
most famous clubs of its time.

01:15:11.550 --> 01:15:15.010
I don't know if all of
you know of it, yeah?

01:15:15.010 --> 01:15:16.720
[ Applause ]

