This was an amazing, amazing
club and it's-- I think it--

01:15:20.670 --> 01:15:24.590
you know, those who knew
about it then were all over it

01:15:24.590 --> 01:15:29.310
but people are just beginning to
find out about Paradise Garage.

01:15:29.310 --> 01:15:32.360
And it had a couple of
things going forward.

01:15:32.360 --> 01:15:36.630
It was a, you know, members club.

01:15:36.630 --> 01:15:42.180
They didn't serve alcohol,
they serve juice and fruit

01:15:42.180 --> 01:15:46.460
but people brought their own
poppers, you know, amyl nitrate

01:15:46.460 --> 01:15:50.310
and alcohol and grass and,
you know, there was plenty

01:15:50.310 --> 01:15:53.300
to get stoned on when
you were there.

01:15:53.300 --> 01:15:57.510
But the great thing about
this club is this guy.

01:15:57.510 --> 01:16:00.840
[ Applause ]

01:16:00.840 --> 01:16:02.190
Larry Levan.

01:16:02.190 --> 01:16:04.950
And there's not-- I don't have
enough time to really talk

01:16:04.950 --> 01:16:09.290
about Larry Levan, it's a whole,
you know, lecture in itself

01:16:09.290 --> 01:16:16.070
because this guy is-- this guy
really created modern DJing

01:16:16.070 --> 01:16:17.380
in a lot of ways.

01:16:17.380 --> 01:16:22.580
And I've spoken to a lot of
DJs today and everybody looks

01:16:22.580 --> 01:16:27.360
at Larry Levan as being pretty
much the major innovator

01:16:27.360 --> 01:16:29.820
of a lot of different styles.

01:16:29.820 --> 01:16:33.810
And he played every kind
of music that he wanted to.

01:16:33.810 --> 01:16:36.620
You know, most of the clubs,
they were handed music

01:16:36.620 --> 01:16:39.270
by the record companies and
said, you now, here's the great,

01:16:39.270 --> 01:16:41.130
hot one to play, you know.

01:16:41.130 --> 01:16:44.890
Larry Levan would look at it and
go, I'll listen to it, you know.

01:16:44.890 --> 01:16:47.510
But he would play rock and
roll, he would play rhythm

01:16:47.510 --> 01:16:50.010
and blues, you know, Motown.

01:16:50.010 --> 01:16:51.380
Pretty much played everything.

01:16:51.380 --> 01:16:54.320
I wasn't there that night
but I heard one night,

01:16:54.320 --> 01:16:58.950
he really liked the Pat Benatar
sone, Love is a Battlefield.

01:16:58.950 --> 01:17:00.510
I don't know if you know that song.

01:17:00.510 --> 01:17:04.350
But he really liked that song so he
played it like 10 times in a row.

01:17:04.350 --> 01:17:06.680
[ Laughter ]

01:17:06.680 --> 01:17:08.870
You know, because he
really liked it.

01:17:08.870 --> 01:17:13.920
And he had a way of really
hypnotizing his audience.

01:17:13.920 --> 01:17:15.220
They loved him.

01:17:15.220 --> 01:17:20.430
They used to call his
playing a Saturday mass,

01:17:20.430 --> 01:17:21.730
they go for Saturday mass.

01:17:21.730 --> 01:17:26.200
It would start at Saturday and
ended like way late Sunday.

01:17:26.200 --> 01:17:31.430
So, these volumes that had
been written about Larry Levan,

01:17:31.430 --> 01:17:35.030
well worth reading about.

01:17:35.030 --> 01:17:40.080
This is what the dance floor
looked like at Paradise Garage,

01:17:40.080 --> 01:17:43.530
mostly Hispanic and
African American.

01:17:43.530 --> 01:17:48.600
Although the thing about
these clubs is that, you know,

01:17:48.600 --> 01:17:53.010
if a white person walked in there,
if a transgender woman walked

01:17:53.010 --> 01:17:56.610
in there, if-- you know,
anybody walked in there,

01:17:56.610 --> 01:18:01.000
it wouldn't have been a problem
but most clubs had their sort

01:18:01.000 --> 01:18:07.590
of like group but it had that
inclusiveness to it, you know.

01:18:07.590 --> 01:18:10.920
This was another one of my
most favorite clubs that a lot

01:18:10.920 --> 01:18:12.440
of people never heard of.

01:18:12.440 --> 01:18:14.650
It's called GG's Barnum Room.

01:18:14.650 --> 01:18:21.720
And it used to be the Peppermint
Lounge where the twists started.

01:18:21.720 --> 01:18:24.210
And after the Peppermint
Lounge closed,

01:18:24.210 --> 01:18:28.310
it turned into GG's Barnum Room
which was a transgender men

01:18:28.310 --> 01:18:30.290
and women's haven basically.

01:18:30.290 --> 01:18:32.300
It was like their club.

01:18:32.300 --> 01:18:34.610
And they had a net
over the dance floor

01:18:34.610 --> 01:18:37.930
and they had the disco
bats performing.

01:18:37.930 --> 01:18:40.860
It was a mixed crowd.

01:18:40.860 --> 01:18:47.280
It was, you know, all
kinds of people went there.

01:18:47.280 --> 01:18:48.580
Yeah, there is too.

01:18:48.580 --> 01:18:58.540
And this is a picture that sort
of become famous from my book.

01:18:58.540 --> 01:19:00.880
It's-- This is a transgender--

01:19:00.880 --> 01:19:05.220
pre-op transgender named Eva
who I actually saw so many times

01:19:05.220 --> 01:19:06.760
when I went there, that
finally we sat down

01:19:06.760 --> 01:19:09.120
and actually had a
long conversation.

01:19:09.120 --> 01:19:10.650
It was very interesting.

01:19:10.650 --> 01:19:16.630
So, you know, a middle class
Jewish boy like myself, sitting,

01:19:16.630 --> 01:19:20.920
talking to a transgender-- pre-op
transgender woman at a club

01:19:20.920 --> 01:19:25.420
like this, it was just, you know,
it was an amazing experience.

01:19:25.420 --> 01:19:27.790
And, you know, I just
learned a lot just

01:19:27.790 --> 01:19:30.940
by doing this, it opened
my mind a lot.

01:19:33.780 --> 01:19:39.020
It became a place where if you're
an out-of-towner, you would stop

01:19:39.020 --> 01:19:42.750
and go to GG's Barnum Room.

01:19:42.750 --> 01:19:45.010
Another club named Crisco Disco.

01:19:45.010 --> 01:19:46.700
[ Laughter ]

01:19:46.700 --> 01:19:53.470 position:56%
Pretty much a gay club but again
became so popular that it became one

01:19:53.470 --> 01:19:57.330
of those, you know, let's stop off
at Crisco Disco before we go home,

01:19:57.330 --> 01:19:59.090
you know, at four in the morning.

01:19:59.090 --> 01:20:03.260
And that Crisco can was the
DJ booth in the back there.

01:20:03.260 --> 01:20:06.120
Another club-- I wanted
to hit all of these clubs.

01:20:06.120 --> 01:20:11.360
So another club is the Mudd
Club, a little applause.

01:20:11.360 --> 01:20:15.810
This was considered an anti-disco.

01:20:15.810 --> 01:20:17.980
They didn't like Studio
54, you know.

01:20:17.980 --> 01:20:19.800
They were political.

01:20:19.800 --> 01:20:23.190
They didn't like the commercialism.

01:20:23.190 --> 01:20:26.080
But it became very, very
popular and they ended up having

01:20:26.080 --> 01:20:31.960
like a velvet rope outside
after awhile too, so.

01:20:31.960 --> 01:20:36.200
This is a famous bathroom
at the Mudd Club.

01:20:36.200 --> 01:20:39.780
And I won't go into the
stories but just trust me,

01:20:39.780 --> 01:20:41.080
it was a famous bathroom.

01:20:41.080 --> 01:20:48.940 position:56%
This is a place called Hurrah's,
which is another kind of anti-disco.

01:20:48.940 --> 01:20:52.260
Also I went to Roller
Disco which was big.

01:20:52.260 --> 01:20:54.720
And Roller Disco was
a place of sweat

01:20:54.720 --> 01:20:57.690
and competition and a lot of fun.

01:20:57.690 --> 01:21:01.240
And if you were a good skater,
you know, you put on your skates

01:21:01.240 --> 01:21:06.650
and you head out for the Empire
Disco in Brooklyn and, you know,

01:21:06.650 --> 01:21:08.860
show everybody your moves.

01:21:08.860 --> 01:21:11.950
And again, it didn't
matter if you were white,

01:21:11.950 --> 01:21:14.230
African American, whatever,
you know.

01:21:14.230 --> 01:21:20.270
It was, you know, it was a
competition and it was fun.

01:21:20.270 --> 01:21:23.040 position:56%
I was a little nervous going here
to tell you the truth because it was

01:21:23.040 --> 01:21:25.470
in a part of Brooklyn
that I didn't know

01:21:25.470 --> 01:21:27.200
and it was mostly African American.

01:21:27.200 --> 01:21:33.620
But the minute I walked in, I was
completely at ease and at home.

01:21:36.810 --> 01:21:38.200
There we go.

01:21:38.200 --> 01:21:43.270
So, a couple of things
happened in like 1979

01:21:43.270 --> 01:21:47.000
that changed the disco scene.

01:21:47.000 --> 01:21:52.180
And I sort of say sometimes
that it ended disco

01:21:52.180 --> 01:21:53.850
but that's not exactly true.

01:21:53.850 --> 01:21:57.340
And there's a writer, Tim Lawrence,
who wrote a book about "Life

01:21:57.340 --> 01:22:04.010
and Death on the New York Dance
Floor" about disco from the '80s

01:22:04.010 --> 01:22:07.160
to I think '80 to '83 and
he describes, you know,

01:22:07.160 --> 01:22:10.150
the fact that it did keep
going and it was still creative

01:22:10.150 --> 01:22:11.450
and it was still happening.

01:22:11.450 --> 01:22:17.490
But the disco that I knew and
the disco that I experienced was

01:22:17.490 --> 01:22:22.120
in my opinion over
in like 1979, 1980.

01:22:22.120 --> 01:22:27.520
The first thing that happened
was Studio 54, the famous coke,

01:22:27.520 --> 01:22:31.830
spoon and moon, they were
closed down by the IRS.

01:22:31.830 --> 01:22:35.890
And what happened was Steve Rubell

01:22:35.890 --> 01:22:40.740
and Ian Schrager were skimming the
cash registers and taking the money

01:22:40.740 --> 01:22:44.610
and putting it in the
ceiling panels of the office.

01:22:44.610 --> 01:22:46.510
You know, they'd come
down every couple hours

01:22:46.510 --> 01:22:47.930
and take the cash out of drawers.

01:22:47.930 --> 01:22:53.840
And Steve Rubell who wasn't
always the most sober person,

01:22:53.840 --> 01:22:58.300
every time I saw him, he
go, "Who are you again?"

01:22:58.300 --> 01:23:01.550
You know, and I met
him all the time.

01:23:01.550 --> 01:23:03.090
"Bill Bernstein from the Voice."

01:23:03.090 --> 01:23:04.490
"Oh, yeah, yeah."

01:23:04.490 --> 01:23:08.210
And so, anyway, so Steve Rubell
one night was being interviewed

01:23:08.210 --> 01:23:11.420
and they-- and he said, "You know,

01:23:11.420 --> 01:23:17.700
if the IRS knew how much money we
really made, they'd shut us down."

01:23:17.700 --> 01:23:23.470
And so guess what happened
about two days later?

01:23:23.470 --> 01:23:28.860
And they went to jail and
that place was shut down.

01:23:28.860 --> 01:23:31.710
It opened up under some new
ownership but, you know,

01:23:31.710 --> 01:23:34.010
to me it was never the same.

01:23:34.010 --> 01:23:41.030
There was a cultural backlash
against disco music, disco culture,

01:23:41.030 --> 01:23:45.200
the rock and rollers
wanted their music back.

01:23:45.200 --> 01:23:48.310
They got sick of disco music.

01:23:48.310 --> 01:23:56.580
And there was a racial overtone to
it that-- you know, is, you know,

01:23:56.580 --> 01:23:59.490
is pretty much clearly there.

01:23:59.490 --> 01:24:04.950
But it was-- there was a racial--
yeah, there was a racial overtone.

01:24:04.950 --> 01:24:14.500
But it-- disco became unpopular
and it became sort of a dirty word.

01:24:14.500 --> 01:24:16.930
So that happened.

01:24:16.930 --> 01:24:23.170
And then in, I believe it was 1981,

01:24:23.170 --> 01:24:27.380
the "New York Times"
published an article saying

01:24:27.380 --> 01:24:33.570
that there was an AIDS epidemic
and that it was spreading.

01:24:33.570 --> 01:24:36.160
And everybody knew
something was going on.

01:24:36.160 --> 01:24:38.570
They called it the gay cancer.

01:24:38.570 --> 01:24:43.300
But they officially
declared it an epidemic.

01:24:43.300 --> 01:24:46.960
And so what happened was
people didn't know anything

01:24:46.960 --> 01:24:49.530
when AIDS was first announced.

01:24:49.530 --> 01:24:53.600
And so they were afraid that
if you're talking to somebody

01:24:53.600 --> 01:24:57.890
and they accidentally like spit
a little and it goes in your eye,

01:24:57.890 --> 01:25:01.400
you could get AIDS or if they were
sweating and you touched them,

01:25:01.400 --> 01:25:04.140
you could get AIDS or
if you shook their hand.

01:25:04.140 --> 01:25:05.940
So, nobody knew anything.

01:25:05.940 --> 01:25:08.410
It was just-- There
was no information.

01:25:08.410 --> 01:25:11.980
And Ronald Reagan came
into power at that point.

01:25:11.980 --> 01:25:14.640
And he didn't want to deal with
AIDS for the first two years

01:25:14.640 --> 01:25:17.900
of his office, his administration.

01:25:17.900 --> 01:25:24.430
So, it just really
affected the whole scene.

01:25:24.430 --> 01:25:29.310 position:56%
And those three things in my opinion
really accounted for, you know,

01:25:29.310 --> 01:25:36.360
shutting down or changing I
should say the whole disco world

01:25:36.360 --> 01:25:38.530
that I knew.

01:25:38.530 --> 01:25:44.250
Real quickly, what happened
was these pictures ended

01:25:44.250 --> 01:25:50.860
up in a box somewhere and they ran
in the Village Voice once in awhile

01:25:50.860 --> 01:25:55.540
but basically I just
put them away like 1979.

01:25:55.540 --> 01:25:59.010
And in about 2003, I got a call
from a guy named David Hill

01:25:59.010 --> 01:26:00.600
in London who's a music producer.

01:26:00.600 --> 01:26:03.630
And he said, "Did you do
these pictures of disco?"

01:26:03.630 --> 01:26:04.930
And I said, "Yeah."

01:26:04.930 --> 01:26:07.750
And he said, "Well, there's a
renewed interest in this period.

01:26:07.750 --> 01:26:10.290
Would you like to do
a coffee table book?"

01:26:10.290 --> 01:26:13.260
So I said, "Yeah, absolutely."

01:26:13.260 --> 01:26:17.190
And so he found a publisher,
Reel Art Press in London

01:26:17.190 --> 01:26:20.060
and Tony Nourmand, the
publisher, and David

01:26:20.060 --> 01:26:23.340
and I started putting
this book together.

01:26:23.340 --> 01:26:27.110
And I was-- this was 2015.

01:26:27.110 --> 01:26:32.350
I realized as we were doing this
that it became crystal clear to me,

01:26:32.350 --> 01:26:37.640
you know, what I had here
because in 2015 the equal marriage

01:26:37.640 --> 01:26:40.320
amendment passed.

01:26:40.320 --> 01:26:45.450
The flag-- The confederate
flag came down in the south,

01:26:45.450 --> 01:26:50.340
transgenders were allowed
in the military.

01:26:50.340 --> 01:26:54.360
It's like there was this sea
change during that year of sort

01:26:54.360 --> 01:26:59.550
of cultural awareness and
acceptance and inclusion.

01:26:59.550 --> 01:27:04.300
And I thought to myself, like
what I captured here was really

01:27:04.300 --> 01:27:07.660
like the beginning, you know.

01:27:07.660 --> 01:27:11.230
Like it was like a small
microcosm of the world

01:27:11.230 --> 01:27:14.140
that we're just beginning
to see today.

01:27:14.140 --> 01:27:18.710
And I sort of feel that, you know,
in cultural movements like this

01:27:18.710 --> 01:27:24.110
that you take two steps
forward and one step backward.

01:27:24.110 --> 01:27:27.620
And I think we might be taking
a step backward right now a

01:27:27.620 --> 01:27:29.230
little bit.

01:27:29.230 --> 01:27:31.440
[ Applause ]

01:27:31.440 --> 01:27:35.240
But I believe in my
heart that inclusion

01:27:35.240 --> 01:27:41.510
and acceptance is a natural way
of being, as a human being, and--

01:27:41.510 --> 01:27:47.530
[ Applause ]

01:27:47.530 --> 01:27:50.570
And I think we're going to move
forward in our culture again.

01:27:50.570 --> 01:27:52.080
So thank you very much.

01:27:52.080 --> 01:27:53.880
I appreciate it.

01:27:53.880 --> 01:28:01.210
[ Applause ]

01:28:01.210 --> 01:28:02.510
Thank you.

01:28:02.510 --> 01:28:05.730
&gt;&gt; Alice Echols: Hello folks.

01:28:05.730 --> 01:28:09.520
Hi, my name is Alice Echols.

01:28:09.520 --> 01:28:12.750
I teach at the University
of Southern California.

01:28:12.750 --> 01:28:16.390
And I wrote a book back in
2010 called the "Hot Stuff,

01:28:16.390 --> 01:28:19.380
Disco and the Remaking
of American Culture".

01:28:19.380 --> 01:28:25.820
And I first of all want to thank
the incredibly competent staff here

01:28:25.820 --> 01:28:27.120
at the Library of Congress.

01:28:27.120 --> 01:28:29.740
They've just been terrific.

01:28:29.740 --> 01:28:36.080
I would like to linger for
a moment on what I consider

01:28:36.080 --> 01:28:39.420
to be the irony of this event.

01:28:39.420 --> 01:28:44.190
An event that really
frankly seemed highly--

01:28:44.190 --> 01:28:46.300
would have seemed highly unlikely

01:28:46.300 --> 01:28:50.530
until I think just even
about 10 years ago.

01:28:50.530 --> 01:28:52.400
I mean, the idea that the Library

01:28:52.400 --> 01:28:56.510
of Congress would be staging
this event, unthinkable.

01:28:56.510 --> 01:29:03.190
[ Applause ]

01:29:03.190 --> 01:29:07.990
You see for those of you who
were too young to remember this,

01:29:07.990 --> 01:29:12.570
disco really was not meant to be
the subject of books and films

01:29:12.570 --> 01:29:15.850
and conferences where
participants would grapple

01:29:15.850 --> 01:29:18.680
with its meaning and its effects.

01:29:18.680 --> 01:29:24.320
You know, disco was supposed to
have been buried some 36 years ago.

01:29:24.320 --> 01:29:29.280
And it's actually true that
by 1981, all across America,

01:29:29.280 --> 01:29:32.910
radio stations were
ditching disco in favor

01:29:32.910 --> 01:29:36.020
of really anything
else, any other format.

01:29:36.020 --> 01:29:41.200
In very many places across the
country, actual disco started

01:29:41.200 --> 01:29:46.560
to shut down, to be
replaced by anything else.

01:29:46.560 --> 01:29:50.130
In 1981, the Grammy Awards dropped.

01:29:50.130 --> 01:29:52.270
It short lived disco category

01:29:52.270 --> 01:29:56.670
after having grudgingly
just established it.

01:29:56.670 --> 01:30:00.920
Gloria Gaynor's "I Will
Survive" remains the only record

01:30:00.920 --> 01:30:05.740
to have been awarded the best
disco recording which had won

01:30:05.740 --> 01:30:09.050
in 1980, and that was that.

01:30:09.050 --> 01:30:11.810
Record labels also
went about shutting

01:30:11.810 --> 01:30:15.700
down their disco divisions
if they had once.

01:30:15.700 --> 01:30:19.980
And soon the record jackets of
those club singles that your DJ,

01:30:19.980 --> 01:30:24.330
if you went to a disco, that
your DJ played changed as well

01:30:24.330 --> 01:30:25.810
and I remember this very clearly

01:30:25.810 --> 01:30:29.530
because I was a DJ in
Ann Arbor, Michigan.

01:30:29.530 --> 01:30:31.290
Yay!

01:30:31.290 --> 01:30:33.750
[ Applause ]

01:30:33.750 --> 01:30:37.450
So, gone were the drawings
of platform shoes

01:30:37.450 --> 01:30:41.360 position:56%
and all those other signifiers of
disco and instead they were replaced

01:30:41.360 --> 01:30:46.580
by graphics that were supposed
to conjure up new wave.

01:30:46.580 --> 01:30:50.730
And really so complete was disco's
banishment from the mainstream

01:30:50.730 --> 01:30:52.350
that it had to be re-branded

01:30:52.350 --> 01:30:58.310
and henceforth it became
known as dance music.

01:30:59.350 --> 01:31:02.980
But a funny thing happened on
the way to the musical graveyard.

01:31:02.980 --> 01:31:06.800
Disco, well disco persisted,
that's--

01:31:08.430 --> 01:31:11.510
thank you, thank you
for [inaudible].

01:31:11.510 --> 01:31:14.720
[ Applause ]

01:31:14.720 --> 01:31:19.180
Yes, this new dance music
employed some of it,

01:31:19.180 --> 01:31:23.560
a less predictable beat
than the 4/4 thump.

01:31:23.560 --> 01:31:27.360
But it sounded an awful
lot like disco.

01:31:27.360 --> 01:31:31.310
Some of the biggest artist of
the 1980s, Madonna, Prince,

01:31:31.310 --> 01:31:34.630
Michael Jackson, cut disco tracks.

01:31:34.630 --> 01:31:38.740
Even if their record companies
studiously avoided ever calling

01:31:38.740 --> 01:31:40.540
it disco.

01:31:40.540 --> 01:31:43.710
And fast forward to today,
and you tell me that Lorde's

01:31:43.710 --> 01:31:48.870
"Green Light" doesn't bear
a distinct depth to disco.

01:31:48.870 --> 01:31:52.800
So, you know, disco
continues to exact its revenge

01:31:52.800 --> 01:31:57.810
through contemporary music
and through events like this.

01:31:57.810 --> 01:32:04.040 position:56%
