you know, there was a lot wrong

02:33:31.610 --> 02:33:35.660
in the 1920s including
the income inequality,

02:33:35.660 --> 02:33:37.760
which we know a little about today.

02:33:37.760 --> 02:33:41.200
And because we have exceeded it.

02:33:41.200 --> 02:33:45.180
But it's certainly true that for
people of color and for women and,

02:33:45.180 --> 02:33:49.800
again, people who in some respects
were on the margins culturally,

02:33:49.800 --> 02:33:54.210
that commodification whether
it was happening in the movies

02:33:54.210 --> 02:33:58.200
or in the spread of
movies, or in the spread

02:33:58.200 --> 02:34:01.020
of department stores could have,

02:34:01.020 --> 02:34:03.670
and I know this again they
seem counterintuitive.

02:34:03.670 --> 02:34:07.450
But it could be used in
ways that were understood

02:34:07.450 --> 02:34:09.660
to be liberatory to those groups.

02:34:09.660 --> 02:34:12.890
So, a lot of scholarship
really debating this.

02:34:12.890 --> 02:34:16.030
It's a very good question.

02:34:16.030 --> 02:34:17.330
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger: Yeah.

02:34:17.330 --> 02:34:22.400
And also, I think-- I just want to
make two sort of additional points

02:34:22.400 --> 02:34:26.050
about that, the one is that
I'm not sure that all forms

02:34:26.050 --> 02:34:29.000
