02:41:57.530 --> 02:41:58.830
&gt;&gt; Right.

02:41:58.830 --> 02:42:00.130
&gt;&gt; Alice Echols: And--

02:42:00.130 --> 02:42:01.430
&gt;&gt; And see that's why--

02:42:01.430 --> 02:42:02.730
&gt;&gt; Alice Echols: -- I mean--

02:42:02.730 --> 02:42:04.030
&gt;&gt; I don't hear it.

02:42:04.030 --> 02:42:05.330
I hear-- I see the
different singers,

02:42:05.330 --> 02:42:06.630
but I'm not-- I'm trying to--

02:42:06.630 --> 02:42:08.970
&gt;&gt; Alice Echols: But I think
that there are some distinctions.

02:42:08.970 --> 02:42:12.210
And again, these really
derived from the music

02:42:12.210 --> 02:42:13.800 position:56%
that was coming out of Philadelphia.

02:42:13.800 --> 02:42:15.100
&gt;&gt; Right. Right.

02:42:15.100 --> 02:42:16.590
&gt;&gt; Alice Echols: Philadelphia
International Records,

02:42:16.590 --> 02:42:19.180
PIR, Gamble and Huff.

02:42:19.180 --> 02:42:20.480
&gt;&gt; Right.

02:42:20.480 --> 02:42:21.860
&gt;&gt; Alice Echols: And they
were creating soul music

02:42:21.860 --> 02:42:24.930
that was washer, it was silkier.

02:42:24.930 --> 02:42:27.400
There were different
instruments being used.

02:42:27.400 --> 02:42:31.850
